postcontent:
Hey guys, looking to sell my AK, since I need to buy an AR for a training program. So, up for sale is my Polish AKM. Made in 1969 at Polish Radom factory, then imported and built by Atlantic Firearms. This is NOT a Century/Tantal/WASR/IO/etc. It's properly assembled and well-put together, as expected from Atlantic Firearms. The rifle is 922r compliant, including a US-made, chrome lined barrel and Tapco G2 trigger. The bolt, carrier, and piston are nickel-plated as well. 

The rifle has less than 1,000 rounds through it and has been meticulously cared for. Furniture is original Polish surplus wood in excellent condition, with an original Bakelite pistol grip, also in great condition. I will include three magazines: one Polish surplus steel 30 rounder, one black Magpul 30 rounder, and one Tula Bakelite 30 rounder. All mags are in good condition. Also included will be an original Polish surplus cleaning kit, oil can, sling, and 3-cell mag pouch (pouch not pictured). Additionally, I'll include an original Polish Bakelite-handled AKM bayonet (with wire-cutter sheath) that fits the rifle. 

All of this will be shipped in a padded rifle case, which will be included at no extra charge. I really hate to see this gun go - it's been my favorite for a long time - but I'll be entering a training program which (unfortunately) requires I own an AR-type rifle and I can't afford to own both right now. I can provide extra pictures of the rifle (inside and out) and more information upon request.

The rifle (with one steel magazine and case) retails new from Atlantic Firearms at $839. I am mildly flexible on price, however, so shoot me an offer and we can probably work something out.

postcontent:
Here is an exceptionally built 1981-S Romanian 11” barreled AK47 Draco Pistol in 7.62x39 cal. built on a NDS-3 Receiver that is 1.6mm thick. This receiver gives you the strength of a milled receiver without all the extra weight. 
Great care was taken, putting this AK pistol together. Would consider it a 98+% gun, and it comes with mag as shown, soft assault case, and a swiveled shoulder strap.

AK mags fit snug with no wobble and release cleanly.

Upper and lower hand guards are also 98+% condition, and as you can see, it is the very nice mahogany darker reddish color, instead of the blondish color you see on most other newer built AK pistols.

This AK47 Draco also has the standard AK style of forward raking gas tube, with a separate attached sight and threaded slant cut muzzle brake on the end. (Also have a different muzzle brake and flash suppressor that will go with the gun.) Again, most other builds incorporate a squared off sight and gas tube combination, and IMO just doesn't look as clean as this style, which you will not see too many of in the AK47 Pistols.

I was going to put a Tapco 2 trigger group in it, but just decided that a double spring and a fluff & buff on the contact areas was all that was needed. Will include the Tapco 2 trigger with it's other items with purchase. 

If you are looking for a quality AK47 Draco pistol, that will give even the best Arsenal AK pistols a run for their money at half the cost, then you better grab this one fast.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Remington Mohawk model 11-48 12 gauge autoloader
postcontent:
I have a 1975 Remington Mohawk-48 for sale or trade.  It is chambered in 12 gauge for 2-3/4 inch shells.  This one has a 30 inch barrel stamped as a full choke, but is also threaded in the tru-choke pattern, so I think it may have been reamed out or just threaded for a mussel-break, I'm really not sure.  It has some surface rust on the barrel from sitting in someone's closet for too long and some wear on the finish.  It cycles just fine and I have the inside of the barrel back to a mirror finish. No abnormal wear, a really decent shotgun, just not what I need.
A little history on these because they're a little uncommon:  They 11-48 was made from around WWII to the 60's when the 11-87 and 1100 took over.  In the 70's they made the Mohawk-48 from the old 11-48 parts, the only difference is the model year.  They are a long recoil design, so the barrel actually recesses into the chamber when it cycles.  The benefit of this is that it eats any kind of ammo without gas adjustment and is reliable in any weather, even dirty.  You can still find the barrels online for around $200, but this barrel is actually in good working condition.  

I picked up this shotgun a few weeks ago on a whim because I wanted a beater for duck hunting from my kayak.  I couldn't forgive myself if I dumped my old Ithica overboard, so I figured I would buy this shotgun.  Anyway, I didn't realized that it wouldn't be able to handle steel shot (stupid me) so now I need to get rid of it and buy something a little newer.  I would like to get my money back on it, so $275 takes it.

You know the drill, residents only, must be legal to buy/own a firearm, have an ID for me at the time of purchase and I would like you to sell a bill of sale because this gun is registered to me.
If you have further questions or need pictures, my phone number is 513-833-seven08three, call or text or email whenever and I'll get back to you ASAP.

title: For Sale:  FIRING LINE not doing pvt prty  transfers for longtime customers
postcontent: I happened to be near Firing Line of Aurora and needed to do a quick private transfer. I have been an occasional customer of this place since the late 80's. This time I walked in with another gun collector and inquired about a transfer. I was told they will not do a private transfer. I then asked to speak to a manager. When I spoke to the manager I informed him I was a repeat customer and I wished to have a private transfer done. He refused. He said the only transfers they would do are for guns they sell. I told him I had bought 3 handguns this year and doing right by me would be in there best interests. He simply said thanks for that and he could not and would not do a private transfer because the owners had decided not to allow them. When I asked about the owners he simply said good day and please leave. This leaves me to believe this "gun shop" is putting their sales or profits above the needs of the common law-abiding gun owners who were not buying their guns. Please take notice of this shop and take patronizing their establishment with a grain of salt. On a second note, the Gander Mountain just down the road, a "big box" store was more then happy to help with the transfer. Thank you for reading this.

title: For Sale:  Trade Pending: I.O. Inc AK47 Sporter w/ 6 Mags, extra Flash Hider, and Cleaning Kit
postcontent:
Thank you for looking.  For sale today is an I.O. Inc AK47 Sporter.  This rifle is made in the USA and carries a lifetime warranty.  Unlike most AK47's, I.O. boasts a 2 MOA accuracy.

Three of the magazines are 30-round Tapco's and three are 30-round I.O.'s, but the I.O.'s tend to bind up past 20 rounds.  I believe the flash hider is also a Tapco.  The slant muzzle brake does a great job of defeating muzzle rise.  I've never had any feeding issues, and the sights appear to be spot on.  This model has a rail section on the left, allowing you to add an over-the-cover scope rail, but I would probably just recommend using a light and a laser on the left side, in my opinion.

Background: This gun is almost new.  The firing pin broke, and the rear sight was loose.  I returned it to I.O. for service, and it returned in about a week.  There is a blemish on the wood as can be seen in the second picture.  The blemish appears to be only the varnish, so it should be very easy to refinish.

Asking $700 for rifle, mags, cleaning kit, and flash hider.  If you have any questions, please feel free to ask.
